# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: animal-product
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:animal-product/advanced-meat-recovery] In the US, products produced by advanced meat recovery machinery can be labeled using terms associated with hand-deboned product (i.e., "beef", "pork", "beef trimmings", etc.).
[src:animal-product/advanced-meat-recovery] USDA regulations for procurement of frozen fresh ground beef products state that "Beef that is mechanically separated from bone with automatic deboning systems, advanced lean (meat) recovery (AMR) systems or powered knives, will not be allowed".
[src:animal-product/advanced-meat-recovery] The equivalent technology is known as "low pressure mechanical meat separation" in the European Union, and its product governed as a subset of mechanically separated meat.
[src:animal-product/advanced-meat-recovery] The product was formerly known as desinewed meat (DSM).
[src:animal-product/advanced-meat-recovery] In the United States, USDA regulations stipulate that AMR machinery cannot grind, crush, or pulverize bones to remove edible meat tissue, and bones must emerge intact.
[src:animal-product/advanced-meat-recovery] The meat produced in this manner can contain no more than 150(±30) milligrams of calcium per 100 grams product, as calcium in such high concentrations in the product would be indicative of bone being mixed with the meat.
[src:animal-product/advanced-meat-recovery] Products that exceed the calcium content limit must instead be labeled "mechanically separated beef or pork" in the ingredients statement.
[src:animal-product/advanced-meat-recovery] In 1994, the Food Safety and Inspection Service (FSIS) issued a rule allowing such meat to be labeled as meat for human consumption, providing that the bones from which it was removed were still intact after processing.
[src:animal-product/advanced-meat-recovery] In 1997, following tests indicating that central nervous system (CNS) tissue was showing up in mechanically removed meat, FSIS issued a directive to its inspectors instructing them to ensure that spinal cord tissue was removed from bones before the AMR process.
[src:animal-product/advanced-meat-recovery] Following the identification of a BSE-infected U.S. dairy cow in December 2003, FSIS issued new regulations expanding the definition of prohibited CNS tissue to include additional cattle parts.
[src:animal-product/advanced-meat-recovery] Furthermore, all AMR-processed product from cattle more than 30 months old now is prohibited from being used for food, and such product from younger cattle and from other livestock species also is prohibited if it contains CNS material.
[src:animal-product/advanced-meat-recovery] The USDA's AMR guidelines restrict the processing of the parts of cattle that may contain central nervous tissue from AMR systems in cattle over 30 months of age.
[src:animal-product/advanced-meat-recovery] However, non-CNS tissue meat can be processed and is considered meat, as are the muscle cuts.
[src:animal-product/advanced-meat-recovery] Although some sources claim AMR systems use ammonia (or anhydrous ammonia, ammonia hydroxide, etc.) to treat the meat, this appears to be due to confusion between AMR and the production of lean finely textured beef (LFTB, commonly referred to as pink slime).
[src:animal-product/advanced-meat-recovery] LFTB is in fact treated with ammonia, and so is substantially more restricted than most AMR products.
[src:animal-product/advanced-meat-recovery] Prior to 2012, desinewed meat (DSM) could be called "meat" in the UK.
[src:animal-product/advanced-meat-recovery] In 2012, European Commission reclassified DSM as a kind of mechanically recovered meat (MRM).
[src:animal-product/advanced-meat-recovery] The downgrade of DSM took effect in the UK in May 2012.
[src:animal-product/advanced-meat-recovery] Unlike other types of MRM, which have the appearance of a paste, DSM resembled minced meat.
[src:animal-product/advanced-meat-recovery] The new regulation treats DSM as "low-pressure mechanically separated meat".
[src:animal-product/advanced-meat-recovery] As a result, many of the regulations governing conventional (high-pressure, paste) MSM/MRM apply, including the 2004 ban on MSM produced from ruminants.
[src:animal-product/advanced-meat-recovery] However, low-pressure MSM is still subject to looser rules in recognition of the lower microbial risk.
[src:animal-product/advanced-meat-recovery] While high-pressure MSM needs to be frozen immediately after production, low-pressure MSM only needs to be chilled.
[src:animal-product/advanced-meat-recovery] Low pressure MSM is also allowed in some uncooked products, while high-pressure MSM is not.
[src:animal-product/agricultural-wastewater-treatment] Nonpoint source pollution includes sediment runoff, nutrient runoff and pesticides.
[src:animal-product/agricultural-wastewater-treatment] Point source pollution includes animal wastes, silage liquor, milking parlour (dairy farming) wastes, slaughtering waste, vegetable washing water and firewater.
[src:animal-product/agricultural-wastewater-treatment] Many farms generate nonpoint source pollution from surface runoff which is not controlled through a treatment plant.
[src:animal-product/agricultural-wastewater-treatment] Farmers can install erosion controls to reduce runoff flows and retain soil on their fields.
[src:animal-product/agricultural-wastewater-treatment] Common techniques include contour plowing, crop mulching, crop rotation, planting perennial crops and installing riparian buffers.
[src:animal-product/agricultural-wastewater-treatment] Farmers can also develop and implement nutrient management plans to reduce excess application of nutrients and reduce the potential for nutrient pollution.
[src:animal-product/agricultural-wastewater-treatment] To minimize pesticide impacts, farmers may use Integrated Pest Management (IPM) techniques (which can include biological pest control) to maintain control over pests, reduce reliance on chemical pesticides, and protect water quality.
[src:animal-product/agricultural-wastewater-treatment] Nonpoint source pollution from farms is caused by surface runoff from fields during rain storms.
[src:animal-product/agricultural-wastewater-treatment] Agricultural runoff is a major source of pollution, in some cases the only source, in many watersheds.
[src:animal-product/agricultural-wastewater-treatment] Soil washed off fields is the largest source of agricultural pollution in the United States.
[src:animal-product/agricultural-wastewater-treatment] Excess sediment causes high levels of turbidity in water bodies, which can inhibit growth of aquatic plants, clog fish gills and smother animal larvae.
[src:animal-product/agricultural-wastewater-treatment] Farmers may utilize erosion controls to reduce runoff flows and retain soil on their fields.
[src:animal-product/agricultural-wastewater-treatment] Nitrogen and phosphorus are key pollutants found in runoff, and they are applied to farmland in several ways, such as in the form of commercial fertilizer, animal manure, or municipal or industrial wastewater (effluent) or sludge.
[src:animal-product/agricultural-wastewater-treatment] These chemicals may also enter runoff from crop residues, irrigation water, wildlife, and atmospheric deposition.
[src:animal-product/agricultural-wastewater-treatment] Pesticides are widely used by farmers to control plant pests and enhance production, but chemical pesticides can also cause water quality problems.
[src:animal-product/agricultural-wastewater-treatment] Some pesticides have also been detected in groundwater.
[src:animal-product/agricultural-wastewater-treatment] Farmers may use Integrated Pest Management (IPM) techniques (which can include biological pest control) to maintain control over pests, reduce reliance on chemical pesticides, and protect water quality.
[src:animal-product/agricultural-wastewater-treatment] There are few safe ways of disposing of pesticide surpluses other than through containment in well managed landfills or by incineration.
[src:animal-product/agricultural-wastewater-treatment] In some parts of the world, spraying on land is a permitted method of disposal.
[src:animal-product/agricultural-wastewater-treatment] Farms with large livestock and poultry operations, such as factory farms, can be a major source of point source wastewater.
[src:animal-product/agricultural-wastewater-treatment] In the United States, these facilities are called concentrated animal feeding operations or *confined animal feeding operations* and are being subject to increasing government regulation.
[src:animal-product/agricultural-wastewater-treatment] Antibiotic-resistant bacteria have been found to infiltrate the water cycle from farms.
[src:animal-product/agricultural-wastewater-treatment] Raising animals accounts for 73% of antibiotics use globally, and wastewater treatment facilities can transfer antibiotic-resistant bacteria to humans.
[src:animal-product/agricultural-wastewater-treatment] Animal wastes from cattle can be produced as solid or semisolid manure or as a liquid slurry.
[src:animal-product/agricultural-wastewater-treatment] The production of slurry is especially common in housed dairy cattle.
[src:animal-product/agricultural-wastewater-treatment] Whilst solid manure heaps outdoors can give rise to polluting wastewaters from runoff, this type of waste is usually relatively easy to treat by containment and/or covering of the heap.
[src:animal-product/agricultural-wastewater-treatment] Animal slurries require special handling and are usually treated by containment in lagoons before disposal by spray or trickle application to grassland.
[src:animal-product/agricultural-wastewater-treatment] Constructed wetlands are sometimes used to facilitate treatment of animal wastes, as are anaerobic lagoons.
[src:animal-product/agricultural-wastewater-treatment] Excessive application or application to sodden land or insufficient land area can result in direct runoff to watercourses, with the potential for causing severe pollution.
[src:animal-product/agricultural-wastewater-treatment] Application of slurries to land overlying aquifers can result in direct contamination or, more commonly, elevation of nitrogen levels as nitrite or nitrate.
[src:animal-product/agricultural-wastewater-treatment] The disposal of any wastewater containing animal waste upstream of a drinking water intake can pose serious health problems to those drinking the water because of the highly resistant spores present in many animals that are capable of causing disabling disease in humans.
[src:animal-product/agricultural-wastewater-treatment] This risk exists even for very low-level seepage via shallow surface drains or from rainfall run-off.
[src:animal-product/agricultural-wastewater-treatment] Some animal slurries are treated by mixing with straws and composted at high temperature to produce a bacteriologically sterile and friable manure for soil improvement.
[src:animal-product/agricultural-wastewater-treatment] Piggery waste is comparable to other animal wastes and is processed as for general animal waste, except that many piggery wastes contain elevated levels of copper that can be toxic in the natural environment.
[src:animal-product/agricultural-wastewater-treatment] The liquid fraction of the waste is frequently separated off and re-used in the piggery to avoid the prohibitively expensive costs of disposing of copper-rich liquid.
[src:animal-product/agricultural-wastewater-treatment] Ascarid worms and their eggs are also common in piggery waste and can infect humans if wastewater treatment is ineffective.
[src:animal-product/agricultural-wastewater-treatment] Fresh or wilted grass or other green crops can be made into a semi-fermented product called silage which can be stored and used as winter forage for cattle and sheep.
[src:animal-product/agricultural-wastewater-treatment] The production of silage often involves the use of an acid conditioner such as sulfuric acid or formic acid.
[src:animal-product/agricultural-wastewater-treatment] The process of silage making frequently produces a yellow-brown strongly smelling liquid which is very rich in simple sugars, alcohol, short-chain organic acids and silage conditioner.
[src:animal-product/agricultural-wastewater-treatment] This liquor is one of the most polluting organic substances known.
[src:animal-product/agricultural-wastewater-treatment] The volume of silage liquor produced is generally in proportion to the moisture content of the ensiled material.
[src:animal-product/agricultural-wastewater-treatment] Silage liquor is best treated through prevention by wilting crops well before silage making.
[src:animal-product/agricultural-wastewater-treatment] Any silage liquor that is produced can be used as part of the food for pigs.
[src:animal-product/agricultural-wastewater-treatment] The most effective treatment is by containment in a slurry lagoon and by subsequent spreading on land following substantial dilution with slurry.
[src:animal-product/agricultural-wastewater-treatment] Containment of silage liquor on its own can cause structural problems in concrete pits because of the acidic nature of silage liquor.
[src:animal-product/agricultural-wastewater-treatment] Although milk is an important food product, its presence in wastewaters is highly polluting because of its organic strength, which can lead to very rapid de-oxygenation of receiving waters.
[src:animal-product/agricultural-wastewater-treatment] Milking parlour wastes also contain large volumes of wash-down water, some animal waste together with cleaning and disinfection chemicals.
[src:animal-product/agricultural-wastewater-treatment] Milking parlour wastes are often treated in admixture with human sewage in a local sewage treatment plant.
[src:animal-product/agricultural-wastewater-treatment] This ensures that disinfectants and cleaning agents are sufficiently diluted and amenable to treatment.
[src:animal-product/agricultural-wastewater-treatment] Running milking wastewaters into a farm slurry lagoon is a possible option although this tends to consume lagoon capacity very quickly.
[src:animal-product/agricultural-wastewater-treatment] Land spreading is also a treatment option.
[src:animal-product/agricultural-wastewater-treatment] Wastewater from slaughtering activities is similar to milking parlour waste (see above) although considerably stronger in its organic composition and therefore potentially much more polluting.
[src:animal-product/agricultural-wastewater-treatment] Treatment is as for milking parlour waste.
[src:animal-product/agricultural-wastewater-treatment] Washing of vegetables produces large volumes of water contaminated by soil and vegetable pieces.
[src:animal-product/agricultural-wastewater-treatment] Low levels of pesticides used to treat the vegetables may also be present together with moderate levels of disinfectants such as chlorine.
[src:animal-product/agricultural-wastewater-treatment] Most vegetable washing waters are extensively recycled with the solids removed by settlement and filtration.
[src:animal-product/agricultural-wastewater-treatment] The recovered soil can be returned to the land.
[src:animal-product/agricultural-wastewater-treatment] Although few farms plan for fires, fires are nevertheless more common on farms than on many other industrial premises.
[src:animal-product/agricultural-wastewater-treatment] Stores of pesticides, herbicides, fuel oil for farm machinery and fertilizers can all help promote fire and can all be present in environmentally lethal quantities in firewater from fire fighting at farms.
[src:animal-product/agricultural-wastewater-treatment] All farm environmental management plans should allow for containment of substantial quantities of firewater and for its subsequent recovery and disposal by specialist disposal companies.
[src:animal-product/agricultural-wastewater-treatment] The concentration and mixture of contaminants in firewater make them unsuited to any treatment method available on the farm.
[src:animal-product/agricultural-wastewater-treatment] Even land spreading has produced severe taste and odour problems for downstream water supply companies in the past.
[src:animal-product/alternative-uses-for-placenta] The placenta is an organ which links the fetus to the mother in mammals for the transfer of oxygen and nutrients to the fetus and fetal waste products to the mother.
[src:animal-product/alternative-uses-for-placenta] Many species of mammals consume their placentas.
[src:animal-product/alternative-uses-for-placenta] Placentas are consumed in some human cultures.
[src:animal-product/alternative-uses-for-placenta] This may be for nutrition but often it has a cultural significance.
[src:animal-product/alternative-uses-for-placenta] For more information about the ritual consumption of placenta see Placenta: Society and culture.
[src:animal-product/alternative-uses-for-placenta] Human and animal placentas are also used as a source of extracts for ingredients in various consumer products such as pharmaceuticals, cosmetics, hair care products, health tonics, and food products other than ritual consumption by the mother or family.
[src:animal-product/alternative-uses-for-placenta] Human placentas are also used by search and rescue teams to train their search and rescue dogs to detect human remains.
[src:animal-product/alternative-uses-for-placenta] At least three companies currently sell hair or skin treatments which contain extracts of animal placenta.
[src:animal-product/alternative-uses-for-placenta] The most common type of placenta used is sheep.
[src:animal-product/alternative-uses-for-placenta] The placental extract allegedly serves as a source of protein and hormones, predominantly estrogen and progesterone, in the cosmetics in which it is used.
[src:animal-product/alternative-uses-for-placenta] The purpose of the placenta extract is not well documented, and information is difficult to find.
[src:animal-product/alternative-uses-for-placenta] The FDA maintains that placenta extract may be hazardous and its use is subject to restrictions and requirements of warnings in at least some products.
[src:animal-product/alternative-uses-for-placenta] In one study, four girls between one and eight years of age developed breasts or pubic hair two to 24 months after starting to use hair products that contained estrogen or placenta extract.
[src:animal-product/alternative-uses-for-placenta] Their breasts and pubic hair regressed when they stopped using the products.
[src:animal-product/alternative-uses-for-placenta] No other cause for early sexual development was noted.
[src:animal-product/alternative-uses-for-placenta] Melsmon Pharmaceutical Co. is a registered pharmaceutical company in Japan, in operation since 1956, that produces pharmaceutical grade placenta extracts from human placenta.
[src:animal-product/alternative-uses-for-placenta] Laennec, another placenta extract formulation, is prescribed to treat chronic hepatitis.
[src:animal-product/alternative-uses-for-placenta] In case of chronic atrophic rhinitis placenta extract is injected to the nasal submucosa.
[src:animal-product/alternative-uses-for-placenta] Albert David Limited a Pharmaceutical company from India also manufactures an Injection from fresh human Placenta called Inj.Placentrex.
[src:animal-product/alternative-uses-for-placenta] Hormone replacement therapy containing estrogen, while protective against osteoporosis, has been found to increase the risk of venous emboli and breast cancer.
[src:animal-product/alternative-uses-for-placenta] As such, the medical community uses hormone replacement therapy only in specific circumstances.
[src:animal-product/alternative-uses-for-placenta] There are a number of foods, many with touted health benefits, that use placenta as an ingredient.
[src:animal-product/alternative-uses-for-placenta] This is in addition to ritual consumption by mothers and families in many cultures.
[src:animal-product/alternative-uses-for-placenta] Plantec Co. in Japan makes a drink called "Placenta Drink" which contains placenta.
[src:animal-product/alternative-uses-for-placenta] The company claims that "It is a drink that used the placenta raw material" [*sic*] and "The expectation that makes the body metabolism active can be done" [*sic*] and "It is a drink of the apple taste" [*sic*].
[src:animal-product/ambergris] Ambergris has been highly valued by perfume makers as a fixative that allows the scent to last much longer, although it has been mostly replaced by synthetic ambroxide.
[src:animal-product/ambergris] Dogs are attracted to the smell of ambergris and are sometimes used by ambergris searchers.
[src:animal-product/ambergris] The English word *amber* derives from Middle Persian ʾmbl, traveling via Arabic *ʿanbar* (عنبر), Middle Latin *ambar*, and Middle French *ambre* to be adopted in Middle English in the 14th century.
[src:animal-product/ambergris] The word "ambergris" comes from the Old French *ambre gris* or "grey amber".
[src:animal-product/ambergris] The addition of "grey" came about when, in the Romance languages, the sense of the word "amber" was extended to Baltic amber (fossil resin), as white or yellow amber (*ambre jaune*), from as early as the late 13th century.
[src:animal-product/ambergris] This fossilised resin subsequently became the dominant (and now exclusive) sense of "amber", leaving "ambergris" as the word for the whale secretion.
[src:animal-product/ambergris] The archaic alternate spelling "ambergrease" arose as an eggcorn from the phonetic pronunciation of "ambergris", encouraged by the substance's waxy texture.
[src:animal-product/ambergris] Ambergris is formed from a secretion of the bile duct in the intestines of the sperm whale, and can be found floating on the sea or washed up on coastlines.
[src:animal-product/ambergris] It is sometimes found in the abdomens of dead sperm whales.
[src:animal-product/ambergris] Because the beaks of giant squids have been discovered within lumps of ambergris, scientists have suggested that the substance is produced by the whale's gastrointestinal tract to ease the passage of hard, sharp objects that it may have eaten.
[src:animal-product/ambergris] It is speculated that an ambergris mass too large to be passed through the intestines is expelled via the mouth, but this remains under debate.
[src:animal-product/ambergris] Another theory states that an ambergris mass is formed when the colon of a whale is enlarged by a blockage from intestinal worms and cephalopod parts resulting in the death of the whale and the mass being excreted into the sea.
[src:animal-product/ambergris] Christopher Kemp, the author of *Floating Gold: A Natural (and Unnatural) History of Ambergris*, says that it is only produced by sperm whales, and only by an estimated one percent of them.
[src:animal-product/ambergris] Ambergris is rare; once expelled by a whale, it often floats for years before making landfall.
[src:animal-product/ambergris] The slim chances of finding ambergris and the legal ambiguity involved led perfume makers away from ambergris, and led chemists to find viable alternatives.
[src:animal-product/ambergris] Ambergris is found primarily in the Atlantic Ocean and on the coasts of South Africa; Brazil; Madagascar; the East Indies; The Maldives; China; Japan; India; Australia; New Zealand; and the Molucca Islands.
[src:animal-product/ambergris] Most commercially collected ambergris comes from the Bahamas in the Atlantic, particularly New Providence.
[src:animal-product/ambergris] In 2021, fishermen found a 127 kg (280-pound) piece of ambergris off the coast of Yemen, valued at US$1.5 million.
[src:animal-product/ambergris] Fossilised ambergris from 1.75 million years ago has also been found.
[src:animal-product/ambergris] Ambergris is found in lumps of various shapes and sizes, usually weighing from 15 grams (1⁄2 ounce) to 50 kilograms (110 pounds) or more.
[src:animal-product/ambergris] When initially expelled by or removed from the whale, the fatty precursor of ambergris is pale white in colour (sometimes streaked with black), soft, with a strong faecal smell.
[src:animal-product/ambergris] Following months to years of photodegradation and oxidation in the ocean, this precursor gradually hardens, developing a dark grey or black colour, a crusty and waxy texture, and a peculiar odour that is at once sweet, earthy, marine, and animalic.
[src:animal-product/ambergris] Its scent has been generally described as a vastly richer and smoother version of isopropanol without its stinging harshness.
[src:animal-product/ambergris] In this developed condition, ambergris has a specific gravity ranging from 0.780 to 0.926 (meaning it floats in water).
[src:animal-product/ambergris] It melts at about 62 °C (144 °F) to a fatty, yellow resinous liquid; and at 100 °C (212 °F) it is volatilised into a white vapour.
[src:animal-product/ambergris] It is soluble in ether, and in volatile and fixed oils.
[src:animal-product/ambergris] Ambergris is relatively nonreactive to acid.
[src:animal-product/ambergris] White crystals of a terpenoid known as ambrein, discovered by Leopold Ružička and Fernand Lardon in 1946, can be separated from ambergris by heating raw ambergris in alcohol, then allowing the resulting solution to cool.
[src:animal-product/ambergris] Breakdown of the relatively scentless ambrein through oxidation produces ambroxide and ambrinol, the main odour components of ambergris.
[src:animal-product/ambergris] Ambroxide is now produced synthetically and used extensively in the perfume industry.
[src:animal-product/ambergris] Ambergris has been mostly known for its use in creating perfume and fragrance much like musk.
[src:animal-product/ambergris] Perfumes based on ambergris still exist.
[src:animal-product/ambergris] The aroma is described as (characteristically) ambergris, animal, marine, seashore.
[src:animal-product/ambergris] Ambergris has historically been used in food and drink.
[src:animal-product/ambergris] A serving of eggs and ambergris was reportedly King Charles II of England's favourite dish.
[src:animal-product/ambergris] A recipe for Rum Shrub liqueur from the mid 19th century called for a thread of ambergris to be added to rum, almonds, cloves, cassia, and the peel of oranges in making a cocktail from *The English and Australian Cookery Book*.
[src:animal-product/ambergris] It has been used as a flavouring agent in Turkish coffee and in hot chocolate in 18th century Europe.
[src:animal-product/ambergris] The substance is considered an aphrodisiac in some cultures.
[src:animal-product/ambergris] Ancient Egyptians burned ambergris as incense, while in modern Egypt ambergris is used for scenting cigarettes.
[src:animal-product/ambergris] Use as an incense can be seen in the John Singer Sargent painting Fumée d'Ambre Gris, painted in Tangiers and Paris in 1880.
[src:animal-product/ambergris] The ancient Chinese called the substance "dragon's spittle fragrance".
[src:animal-product/ambergris] During the Black Death in Europe, people believed that carrying a ball of ambergris could help prevent them from contracting plague.
[src:animal-product/ambergris] This was because the fragrance covered the smell of the air which was believed to be a cause of plague.
[src:animal-product/ambergris] During the Middle Ages, Europeans used ambergris as a medication for headaches, colds, epilepsy, and other ailments.
[src:animal-product/ambergris] In New Zealand, ambergris found washed up on the shores was used by Māori as chewing gum in pre-colonial times.
[src:animal-product/ambergris] From the 18th to the mid-19th century, the whaling industry prospered.
[src:animal-product/ambergris] By some reports, nearly 50,000 whales, including sperm whales, were killed each year.
[src:animal-product/ambergris] Throughout the 19th century, "millions of whales were killed for their oil, whalebone, and ambergris" to fuel profits, and they soon became endangered as a species as a result.
[src:animal-product/ambergris] Because studies showed that the whale populations were being threatened, the International Whaling Commission instituted a moratorium on commercial whaling in 1982.
[src:animal-product/ambergris] Although ambergris is not harvested from whales, many countries also ban the trade of ambergris as part of the more general ban on the hunting and exploitation of whales.
[src:animal-product/ambergris] Urine, faeces, and ambergris (that has been naturally excreted by a sperm whale) are waste products not considered parts or derivatives of a CITES species and are therefore not covered by the provisions of the convention.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] Anaerobic digestion reduces sludge volume and pathogen content while generating methane-rich biogas that can be used for renewable energy production.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] The liquid remainder, digestate can be further treated and, in some cases, beneficially reused.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] Anaerobic digestion occurs naturally in some soils and in lake and oceanic basin sediments, where it is usually referred to as "anaerobic activity".
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] This is the source of marsh gas methane as discovered by Alessandro Volta in 1776.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] The digestion process begins with bacterial hydrolysis of the input materials.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] Insoluble organic polymers, such as carbohydrates, are broken down to soluble derivatives that become available for other bacteria.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] Acidogenic bacteria then convert the sugars and amino acids into carbon dioxide, hydrogen, ammonia, and organic acids.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] In acetogenesis, bacteria convert these resulting organic acids into acetic acid, along with additional ammonia, hydrogen, and carbon dioxide amongst other compounds.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] Finally, methanogens convert these products to methane and carbon dioxide.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] The methanogenic archaea populations play an indispensable role in anaerobic wastewater treatments.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] Anaerobic digestion is used as part of the process to treat biodegradable waste and sewage sludge.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] As part of an integrated waste management system, anaerobic digestion reduces the emission of landfill gas into the atmosphere.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] Anaerobic digesters can also be fed with purpose-grown energy crops, such as maize.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] Anaerobic digestion is widely used as a source of renewable energy.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] The process produces a biogas, consisting of methane, carbon dioxide, and traces of other 'contaminant' gases.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] This biogas can be used directly as fuel, in combined heat and power gas engines or upgraded to natural gas-quality biomethane.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] The nutrient-rich digestate also produced can be used as fertilizer.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] Many microorganisms affect anaerobic digestion, including acetic acid-forming bacteria (acetogens) and methane-forming archaea (methanogens).
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] These organisms promote a number of chemical processes in converting the biomass to biogas.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] Gaseous oxygen is excluded from the reactions by physical containment.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] Anaerobes utilize electron acceptors from sources other than oxygen gas.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] These acceptors can be the organic material itself or may be supplied by inorganic oxides from within the input material.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] When the oxygen source in an anaerobic system is derived from the organic material itself, the 'intermediate' end products are primarily alcohols, aldehydes, and organic acids, plus carbon dioxide.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] In the presence of specialised methanogens, the intermediates are converted to the 'final' end products of methane, carbon dioxide, and trace levels of hydrogen sulfide.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] In an anaerobic system, the majority of the chemical energy contained within the starting material is released by methanogenic archaea as methane.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] Populations of anaerobic microorganisms typically take a significant period of time to establish themselves to be fully effective.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] Therefore, common practice is to introduce anaerobic microorganisms from materials with existing populations, a process known as "seeding" the digesters, typically accomplished with the addition of sewage sludge or cattle slurry.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] The four key stages of anaerobic digestion involve hydrolysis, acidogenesis, acetogenesis and methanogenesis.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] The overall process can be described by the chemical reaction, where organic material such as glucose is biochemically digested into carbon dioxide (CO2) and methane (CH4) by the anaerobic microorganisms.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] In most cases, biomass is made up of large organic polymers.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] For the bacteria in anaerobic digesters to access the energy potential of the material, these chains must first be broken down into their smaller constituent parts.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] These constituent parts, or monomers, such as sugars, are readily available to other bacteria.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] The process of breaking these chains and dissolving the smaller molecules into solution is called hydrolysis.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] Therefore, hydrolysis of these high-molecular-weight polymeric components is the necessary first step in anaerobic digestion.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] Acetate and hydrogen produced in the first stages can be used directly by methanogens.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] into compounds that can be directly used by methanogens.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] results in further breakdown of the remaining components by acidogenic (fermentative) bacteria.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] Here, simple molecules created through the acidogenesis phase are further digested by acetogens to produce largely acetic acid, as well as carbon dioxide and hydrogen.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] Here, methanogens use the intermediate products of the preceding stages and convert them into methane, carbon dioxide, and water.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] These components make up the majority of the biogas emitted from the system.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] Methanogenesis is sensitive to both high and low pHs and occurs between pH 6.5 and pH 8.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] The remaining, indigestible material the microbes cannot use and any dead bacterial remains constitute the digestate.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] Process performance depends on several operational parameters, including temperature (mesophilic conditions at approximately 35–37 °C or thermophilic conditions at 50–55 °C), organic loading rate (OLR), pH (typically maintained between 6.8 and 7.2), and solids retention time (SRT).
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] Proper control of these parameters is essential to prevent process instability and volatile fatty acid accumulation.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] Anaerobic digesters can be designed and engineered to operate using a number of different configurations and can be categorized into batch vs. continuous process mode, mesophilic vs. thermophilic temperature conditions, high vs. low portion of solids, and single stage vs. multistage processes.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] Higher heat energy is required in a thermophilic system compared to a mesophilic system, but the thermophilic system requires much less time and has a larger gas output capacity and higher methane gas content, so one has to consider that trade-off carefully.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] For solids content, low will handle up to 15% solid content.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] Above this level is considered high solids content and can also be known as dry digestion.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] In a single stage process, one reactor houses the four anaerobic digestion steps.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] A multistage process utilizes two or more reactors for digestion to separate the methanogenesis and hydrolysis phases.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] Anaerobic digestion can be performed as a batch process or a continuous process.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] In a batch system, biomass is added to the reactor at the start of the process.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] The reactor is then sealed for the duration of the process.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] In its simplest form batch processing needs inoculation with already processed material to start the anaerobic digestion.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] In a typical scenario, biogas production will be formed with a normal distribution pattern over time.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] Operators can use this fact to determine when they believe the process of digestion of the organic matter has completed.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] There can be severe odour issues if a batch reactor is opened and emptied before the process is well completed.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] A more advanced type of batch approach has limited the odour issues by integrating anaerobic digestion with in-vessel composting.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] In this approach inoculation takes place through the use of recirculated degasified percolate.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] After anaerobic digestion has completed, the biomass is kept in the reactor which is then used for in-vessel composting before it is opened As the batch digestion is simple and requires less equipment and lower levels of design work, it is typically a cheaper form of digestion.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] Using more than one batch reactor at a plant can ensure constant production of biogas.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] In continuous digestion processes, organic matter is constantly added (continuous complete mixed) or added in stages to the reactor (continuous plug flow; first in – first out).
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] Here, the end products are constantly or periodically removed, resulting in constant production of biogas.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] A single or multiple digesters in sequence may be used.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] Examples of this form of anaerobic digestion include continuous stirred-tank reactors, upflow anaerobic sludge blankets, expanded granular sludge beds, and internal circulation reactors.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] A limit case has been reached in Bolivia, with anaerobic digestion in temperature working conditions of less than 10 °C.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] The anaerobic process is very slow, taking more than three times the normal mesophilic time process.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] In experimental work at University of Alaska Fairbanks, a 1,000-litre digester using psychrophiles harvested from "mud from a frozen lake in Alaska" has produced 200–300 litres of methane per day, about 20 to 30% of the output from digesters in warmer climates.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] Mesophilic species outnumber thermophiles, and they are also more tolerant to changes in environmental conditions than thermophiles.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] Mesophilic systems are, therefore, considered to be more stable than thermophilic digestion systems.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] In contrast, while thermophilic digestion systems are considered less stable, their energy input is higher, with more biogas being removed from the organic matter in an equal amount of time.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] The increased temperatures facilitate faster reaction rates, and thus faster gas yields.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] Operation at higher temperatures facilitates greater pathogen reduction of the digestate.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] In countries where legislation, such as the Animal By-Products Regulations in the European Union, requires digestate to meet certain levels of pathogen reduction there may be a benefit to using thermophilic temperatures instead of mesophilic.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] Additional pre-treatment can be used to reduce the necessary retention time to produce biogas.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] For example, certain processes shred the substrates to increase the surface area or use a thermal pretreatment stage (such as pasteurisation) to significantly enhance the biogas output.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] The pasteurisation process can also be used to reduce the pathogenic concentration in the digestate, leaving the anaerobic digester.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] Pasteurisation may be achieved by heat treatment combined with maceration of the solids.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] High solids (dry) digesters are designed to process materials with a solids content between 25 and 40%.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] Unlike wet digesters that process pumpable slurries, high solids (dry – stackable substrate) digesters are designed to process solid substrates without the addition of water.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] The primary styles of dry digesters are continuous vertical plug flow and batch tunnel horizontal digesters.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] Continuous vertical plug flow digesters are upright, cylindrical tanks where feedstock is continuously fed into the top of the digester, and flows downward by gravity during digestion.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] In batch tunnel digesters, the feedstock is deposited in tunnel-like chambers with a gas-tight door.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] Neither approach has mixing inside the digester.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] The amount of pretreatment, such as contaminant removal, depends both upon the nature of the waste streams being processed and the desired quality of the digestate.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] Size reduction (grinding) is beneficial in continuous vertical systems, as it accelerates digestion, while batch systems avoid grinding and instead require structure (e.g. yard waste) to reduce compaction of the stacked pile.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] Continuous vertical dry digesters have a smaller footprint due to the shorter effective retention time and vertical design.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] Wet digesters can be designed to operate in either a high-solids content, with a total suspended solids (TSS) concentration greater than ~20%, or a low-solids concentration less than ~15%.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] High solids (wet) digesters process a thick slurry that requires more energy input to move and process the feedstock.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] The thickness of the material may also lead to associated problems with abrasion.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] High solids digesters will typically have a lower land requirement due to the lower volumes associated with the moisture.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] High solids digesters also require correction of conventional performance calculations (e.g. gas production, retention time, kinetics, etc.) originally based on very dilute sewage digestion concepts, since larger fractions of the feedstock mass are potentially convertible to biogas.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] Low solids (wet) digesters can transport material through the system using standard pumps that require significantly lower energy input.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] Low solids digesters require a larger amount of land than high solids due to the increased volumes associated with the increased liquid-to-feedstock ratio of the digesters.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] There are benefits associated with operation in a liquid environment, as it enables more thorough circulation of materials and contact between the bacteria and their food.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] This enables the bacteria to more readily access the substances on which they are feeding, and increases the rate of gas production.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] Digestion systems can be configured with different levels of complexity.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] In a **single-stage digestion system** (one-stage), all of the biological reactions occur within a single, sealed reactor or holding tank.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] Using a single stage reduces construction costs, but results in less control of the reactions occurring within the system.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] Acidogenic bacteria, through the production of acids, reduce the pH of the tank.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] Methanogenic archaea, as outlined earlier, operate in a strictly defined pH range.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] Therefore, the biological reactions of the different species in a single-stage reactor can be in direct competition with each other.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] Another one-stage reaction system is an anaerobic lagoon.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] These lagoons are pond-like, earthen basins used for the treatment and long-term storage of manures.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] Here the anaerobic reactions are contained within the natural anaerobic sludge contained in the pool.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] In a **two-stage digestion system** (multistage), different digestion vessels are optimised to bring maximum control over the bacterial communities living within the digesters.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] Acidogenic bacteria produce organic acids and more quickly grow and reproduce than methanogenic archaea.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] Methanogenic archaea require stable pH and temperature to optimise their performance.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] Under typical circumstances, hydrolysis, acetogenesis, and acidogenesis occur within the first reaction vessel.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] The organic material is then heated to the required operational temperature (either mesophilic or thermophilic) prior to being pumped into a methanogenic reactor.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] The initial hydrolysis or acidogenesis tanks prior to the methanogenic reactor can provide a buffer to the rate at which feedstock is added.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] Some European countries require a degree of elevated heat treatment to kill harmful bacteria in the input waste.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] In this instance, there may be a pasteurisation or sterilisation stage prior to digestion or between the two digestion tanks.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] Notably, it is not possible to completely isolate the different reaction phases, and often some biogas is produced in the hydrolysis or acidogenesis tanks.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] The residence time in a digester varies with the amount and type of feed material, and with the configuration of the digestion system.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] In a typical two-stage mesophilic digestion, residence time varies between 15 and 40 days, while for a single-stage thermophilic digestion, residence times is normally faster and takes around 14 days.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] The plug-flow nature of some of these systems will mean the full degradation of the material may not have been realised in this timescale.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] In this event, digestate exiting the system will be darker in colour and will typically have more odour.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] In the case of an upflow anaerobic sludge blanket digestion (UASB), hydraulic residence times can be as short as 1 hour to 1 day, and solid retention times can be up to 90 days.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] In this manner, a UASB system is able to separate solids and hydraulic retention times with the use of a sludge blanket.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] Continuous digesters have mechanical or hydraulic devices, depending on the level of solids in the material, to mix the contents, enabling the bacteria and the food to be in contact.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] They also allow excess material to be continuously extracted to maintain a reasonably constant volume within the digestion tanks.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] A recent development in anaerobic reactor design is High-pressure anaerobic digestion (HPAD) also referred to an Autogenerative High Pressure Digestion (AHPD).
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] This technique produces a biogas with an elevated methane content.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] The produced carbon dioxide in biogas dissolves more into the water phase under pressure than methane does.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] Hence the produced biogas is richer in methane.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] Research at the University of Groningen demonstrated that the bacterial community changes in composition under the influence of pressure.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] Individual bacteria species have their optimum circumstances in which they grow and replicate the fastest.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] Commonly known are pH, temperature, salinity etc. but pressure is also one of them.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] Some species have adapted to life in the deep oceans where pressure is much higher than at sea level.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] This makes it possible in similar vein as other process parameters such as Temperature, Retention Time, pH to influence the anaerobic digestion process.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] in Germany, 2007 - the green, inflatable biogas holder is shown on top of the digester.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] The anaerobic digestion process can be inhibited by several compounds, affecting one or more of the bacterial groups responsible for the different organic matter degradation steps.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] The degree of the inhibition depends, among other factors, on the concentration of the inhibitor in the digester.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] Potential inhibitors are ammonia, sulfide, light metal ions (Na, K, Mg, Ca, Al), heavy metals, some organics (chlorophenols, halogenated aliphatics, N-substituted aromatics, long chain fatty acids), etc.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] Total ammonia nitrogen (TAN) has been shown to inhibit production of methane.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] Furthermore, it destabilises the microbial community, impacting the synthesis of acetic acid.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] Acetic acid is one of the driving forces in methane production.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] At an excess of 5000 mg/L TAN, pH adjustment is needed to keep the reaction stable.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] A TAN concentration above 1700– 1800 mg/L inhibits methane production and yield decreases at greater TAN concentrations.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] High TAN concentrations cause the reaction to turn acidic and lead to a domino effect of inhibition.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] Total ammonia nitrogen is the combination of free ammonia and ionized ammonia.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] TAN is produced through degrading material high in nitrogen, typically proteins and will naturally build in anaerobic digestion.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] This is depending on the organic feed stock fed to the system.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] In typical wastewater treatment practices, TAN reduction is done with via nitrification.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] Nitrification is an aerobic process where TAN is consumed by aerobic heterotrophic bacteria.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] These bacteria release nitrate and nitrite which are later converted to nitrogen gas through the denitrification process.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] Hydrolysis and acidogenesis can also be impacted by TAN concentration.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] In mesophilic conditions, inhibition for hydrolysis was found to occur at 5500 mg/L TAN, while acidogenesis inhibition occurs at 6500 mg/L TAN.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] The most important initial issue when considering the application of anaerobic digestion systems is the feedstock to the process.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] Almost any organic material can be processed with anaerobic digestion however, if biogas production is the aim, the level of putrescibility is the key factor in its successful application.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] The more putrescible (digestible) the material, the higher the gas yields possible from the system.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] Feedstocks can include biodegradable waste materials, such as waste paper, grass clippings, leftover food, sewage, and animal waste.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] Woody wastes are the exception, because they are largely unaffected by digestion, as most anaerobes are unable to degrade lignin.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] Xylophagous anaerobes (lignin consumers) or high temperature pretreatment, such as pyrolysis, can be used to break lignin down.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] Anaerobic digesters can also be fed with specially grown energy crops, such as silage, for dedicated biogas production.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] In Germany and continental Europe, these facilities are referred to as "biogas" plants.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] A codigestion or cofermentation plant is typically an agricultural anaerobic digester that accepts two or more input materials for simultaneous digestion.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] The length of time required for anaerobic digestion depends on the chemical complexity of the material.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] Material rich in easily digestible sugars breaks down quickly, whereas intact lignocellulosic material rich in cellulose and hemicellulose polymers can take much longer to break down.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] Anaerobic microorganisms are generally unable to break down lignin, the recalcitrant aromatic component of biomass.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] Anaerobic digesters were originally designed for operation using sewage sludge and manures.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] Sewage and manure are not, however, the material with the most potential for anaerobic digestion, as the biodegradable material has already had much of the energy content taken out by the animals that produced it.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] Therefore, many digesters operate with codigestion of two or more types of feedstock.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] Digesters processing dedicated energy crops can achieve high levels of degradation and biogas production.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] A second consideration related to the feedstock is moisture content.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] Drier, stackable substrates, such as food and yard waste, are suitable for digestion in tunnel-like chambers.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] Tunnel-style systems typically have near-zero wastewater discharge, as well, so this style of system has advantages where the discharge of digester liquids are a liability.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] The wetter the material, the more suitable it will be to handling with standard pumps instead of energy-intensive concrete pumps and physical means of movement.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] Also, the wetter the material, the more volume and area it takes up relative to the levels of gas produced.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] The moisture content of the target feedstock will also affect what type of system is applied to its treatment.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] To use a high-solids anaerobic digester for dilute feedstocks, bulking agents, such as compost, should be applied to increase the solids content of the input material.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] Another key consideration is the carbon:nitrogen ratio of the input material.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] This ratio is the balance of food a microbe requires to grow; the optimal C:N ratio is 20–30:1.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] Excess N can lead to ammonia inhibition of digestion.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] The level of contamination of the feedstock material is a key consideration when using wet digestion or plug-flow digestion.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] If the feedstock to the digesters has significant levels of physical contaminants, such as plastic, glass, or metals, then processing to remove the contaminants will be required for the material to be used.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] If it is not removed, then the digesters can be blocked and will not function efficiently.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] This contamination issue does not occur with dry digestion or solid-state anaerobic digestion (SSAD) plants, since SSAD handles dry, stackable biomass with a high percentage of solids (40-60%) in gas-tight chambers called fermenter boxes.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] It is with this understanding that mechanical biological treatment plants are designed.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] The higher the level of pretreatment a feedstock requires, the more processing machinery will be required, and, hence, the project will have higher capital costs.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] After sorting or screening to remove any physical contaminants from the feedstock, the material is often shredded, minced, and mechanically or hydraulically pulped to increase the surface area available to microbes in the digesters and, hence, increase the speed of digestion.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] The maceration of solids can be achieved by using a chopper pump to transfer the feedstock material into the airtight digester, where anaerobic treatment takes place.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] Substrate composition is a major factor in determining the methane yield and methane production rates from the digestion of biomass.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] Techniques to determine the compositional characteristics of the feedstock are available, while parameters such as solids, elemental, and organic analyses are important for digester design and operation.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] Methane yield can be estimated from the elemental composition of substrate along with an estimate of its degradability (the fraction of the substrate that is converted to biogas in a reactor).
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] Direct measurements of biomethanation potential are also made using gas evolution or more recent gravimetric assays.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] Anaerobic digestion is particularly suited to organic material, and is commonly used for industrial effluent, wastewater and sewage sludge treatment.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] Anaerobic digestion, a simple process, can greatly reduce the amount of organic matter which might otherwise be destined to be dumped at sea, dumped in landfills, or burnt in incinerators.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] Pressure from environmentally related legislation on solid waste disposal methods in developed countries has increased the application of anaerobic digestion as a process for reducing waste volumes and generating useful byproducts.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] It may either be used to process the source-separated fraction of municipal waste or alternatively combined with mechanical sorting systems, to process residual mixed municipal waste.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] These facilities are called mechanical biological treatment plants.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] If the putrescible waste processed in anaerobic digesters were disposed of in a landfill, it would break down naturally and often anaerobically.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] In this case, the gas will eventually escape into the atmosphere.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] As methane is about 20 times more potent as a greenhouse gas than carbon dioxide, this has significant negative environmental effects.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] In countries that collect household waste, the use of local anaerobic digestion facilities can help to reduce the amount of waste that requires transportation to centralized landfill sites or incineration facilities.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] This reduced burden on transportation reduces carbon emissions from the collection vehicles.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] If localized anaerobic digestion facilities are embedded within an electrical distribution network, they can help reduce the electrical losses associated with transporting electricity over a national grid.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] Anaerobic digestion can be used for the remediation of sludge polluted with PFAS.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] A 2024 study has shown that anaerobic digestion, combined with adsorption in activated carbon and voltage application can remove up to 61% of PFAS from sewage sludge.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] In developing countries, simple home and farm-based anaerobic digestion systems offer the potential for low-cost energy for cooking and lighting.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] From 1975, China and India have both had large, government-backed schemes for adaptation of small biogas plants for use in the household for cooking and lighting.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] At present, projects for anaerobic digestion in the developing world can gain financial support through the United Nations Clean Development Mechanism if they are able to show they provide reduced carbon emissions.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] Methane and power produced in anaerobic digestion facilities can be used to replace energy derived from fossil fuels, and hence reduce emissions of greenhouse gases, because the carbon in biodegradable material is part of a carbon cycle.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] The carbon released into the atmosphere from the combustion of biogas has been removed by plants for them to grow in the recent past, usually within the last decade, but more typically within the last growing season.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] If the plants are regrown, taking the carbon out of the atmosphere once more, the system will be carbon neutral.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] In contrast, carbon in fossil fuels has been sequestered in the earth for many millions of years, the combustion of which increases the overall levels of carbon dioxide in the atmosphere.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] Power generation through anaerobic digesters is best suited to large-scale operations, rather than small farms, as large operations have the volume of manure that is able to make the systems financially viable.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] Biogas from sewage sludge treatment is sometimes used to run a gas engine to produce electrical power, some or all of which can be used to run the sewage works.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] Some waste heat from the engine is then used to heat the digester.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] The waste heat is, in general, enough to heat the digester to the required temperatures.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] The power potential from sewage works is limited – in the UK, there are about 80 MW total of such generation, with the potential to increase to 150 MW, which is insignificant compared to the average power demand in the UK of about 35,000 MW.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] The scope for biogas generation from nonsewage waste biological matter – energy crops, food waste, abattoir waste, etc. - is much higher, estimated to be capable of about 3,000 MW.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] Farm biogas plants using animal waste and energy crops are expected to contribute to reducing CO2 emissions and strengthen the grid, while providing UK farmers with additional revenues.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] Some countries offer incentives in the form of, for example, feed-in tariffs for feeding electricity onto the power grid to subsidize green energy production.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] In Oakland, California at the East Bay Municipal Utility District's main wastewater treatment plant (EBMUD), food waste is currently codigested with primary and secondary municipal wastewater solids and other high-strength wastes.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] Compared to municipal wastewater solids digestion alone, food waste codigestion has many benefits.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] Anaerobic digestion of food waste pulp from the EBMUD food waste process provides a higher normalized energy benefit, compared to municipal wastewater solids: 730 to 1,300 kWh per dry ton of food waste applied compared to 560 to 940 kWh per dry ton of municipal wastewater solids applied.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] The methane component of biogas can be concentrated through upgrading into biomethane.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] Biomethane (also known as renewable natural gas) can be injected into the natural gas grid.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] The upgrading process removes contaminants such as hydrogen sulphide and siloxanes, as well as non-methane gas constituents, chiefly carbon dioxide.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] Several technologies are available for this purpose, the most widely implemented being pressure swing adsorption (PSA), water or amine scrubbing (absorption processes) and membrane separation.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] After upgrading with the above-mentioned technologies, biomethane can be compressed into compressed natural gas and used in natural gas vehicles.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] Use of natural gas vehicles is very extensive in Sweden, where over 38,600 gas vehicles exist, and 60% of the CNG supply is biomethane generated in anaerobic digestion plants.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] The solid, fibrous component of the digested material can be used as a soil conditioner to increase the organic content of soils.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] Digester liquor can be used as a fertiliser to supply vital nutrients to soils instead of chemical fertilisers that require large amounts of energy to produce and transport.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] The use of manufactured fertilisers is, therefore, more carbon-intensive than the use of anaerobic digester liquor fertiliser.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] In countries such as Spain, where many soils are organically depleted, the markets for the digested solids can be equally as important as the biogas.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] Anaerobic digestion can be used at a small scale to produce gas for cooking.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] The organic waste like fallen leaves, kitchen waste, food waste etc. are fed into a crusher unit, where it is mixed with a small amount of water.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] The mixture is then fed into the anaerobic digester, where the archaea decomposes it to produce cooking gas.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] A 2 cubic meter anaerobic digester can produce 2 cubic meters of cooking gas.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] The three principal products of anaerobic digestion are biogas, digestate, and water.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] Biogas is the ultimate waste product of the microbes feeding off the input biodegradable feedstock and is mostly methane and carbon dioxide, with a small amount of hydrogen (H 2), water vapor (H 2O, amount depending on temperature), and trace hydrogen sulfide (H 2S).
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] Most of the biogas is produced during the middle of the digestion, after the bacterial population has grown, and tapers off as the putrescible material is exhausted.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] The gas is normally stored on top of the digester in an inflatable gas bubble or extracted and stored next to the facility in a gas holder.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] The methane in biogas can be burned to produce both heat and electricity, usually with a reciprocating engine or microturbine often in a cogeneration arrangement where the electricity and waste heat generated are used to warm the digesters or to heat buildings.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] Excess electricity can be sold to suppliers or put into the local grid.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] Electricity produced by anaerobic digesters is considered to be renewable energy and may attract subsidies.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] Biogas does not contribute to increasing atmospheric carbon dioxide concentrations because the gas is not released directly into the atmosphere and the carbon dioxide comes from an organic source with a short carbon cycle.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] Biogas may require treatment or 'scrubbing' to refine it for use as a fuel.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] Hydrogen sulfide, a toxic product formed from sulfates in the feedstock, is released as a trace component of the biogas.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] National environmental enforcement agencies, such as the U.S.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] Alternatively, the addition of ferrous chloride FeCl2 to the digestion tanks inhibits hydrogen sulfide production.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] Volatile siloxanes can also contaminate the biogas; such compounds are frequently found in household waste and wastewater.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] In digestion facilities accepting these materials as a component of the feedstock, low-molecular-weight siloxanes volatilise into biogas.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] When this gas is combusted in a gas engine, turbine, or boiler, siloxanes are converted into silicon dioxide (SiO2), which deposits internally in the machine, increasing wear and tear.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] Practical and cost-effective technologies to remove siloxanes and other biogas contaminants are available at the present time.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] In certain applications, *in situ* treatment can be used to increase the methane purity by reducing the offgas carbon dioxide content, purging the majority of it in a secondary reactor.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] In countries such as Switzerland, Germany, and Sweden, the methane in the biogas may be compressed for it to be used as a vehicle transportation fuel or input directly into the gas mains.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] In countries where the driver for the use of anaerobic digestion are renewable electricity subsidies, this route of treatment is less likely, as energy is required in this processing stage and reduces the overall levels available to sell.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] Digestate is the non-gaseous product of the digesters.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] It consists of remnants of the original input material to the digesters that the microbes cannot use and the mineralised remains of the dead bacteria from within the digesters.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] The acidogenic and methanogenic steps each produce a digestate product, which are fibrous and liquid respectively.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] In two-stage systems, different forms of digestate come from different digestion tanks.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] In single-stage digestion systems, the two fractions appear combined into a sludge and, if desired, can be separated by further processing.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] The acidogenic digestate is a stable, organic, fiborous material consisting largely of lignin and cellulose, but also of a variety of mineral components in a matrix of dead bacterial cells; some plastic may be present.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] The material resembles domestic compost and can be used as such.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] It can also be used as a lignocellulosic biomass to make low-grade building products such as fibreboard. or as feedstock for ethanol production.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] The methanogenic digestate is a liquid rich in plant nutrients (nitrogen as ammoniums and potassium), which can be used as a fertiliser, depending on the quality of the material being digested.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] Levels of potentially toxic elements (PTEs) should be chemically assessed.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] This will depend upon the quality of the original feedstock.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] In the case of most clean and source-separated biodegradable waste streams, the levels of PTEs will be low.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] In the case of wastes originating from industry, the levels of PTEs may be higher and will need to be taken into consideration when determining a suitable end use for the material.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] Acidogenic digestate typically contains biopolymers, such as lignin, that cannot be broken down by the anaerobic microorganisms.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] Methanogenic digestate may contain ammonia at phytotoxic levels and may hamper the growth of plants if it is used as a soil-improving material.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] For these two reasons, a maturation or composting stage may be employed after digestion.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] Lignin and other materials are available for degradation by aerobic microorganisms such as fungi.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] During maturation, ammonia is oxidized into nitrates which improves the fertility of the material as a soil amendment.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] In addition, composting leads to significant mass loss (primarily through evaporation) reducing the amount of material that needs to be trucked off-site.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] Composting is often used in dry digesters, as wet digesters require bulking with wood products or other material to be compostable.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] As most digesters are unable to degrade compostable packaging, secondary composting is required for this sort of packaging to be processed in an anaerobic digester.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] The final output from anaerobic digestion systems is water, which originates both from the moisture content of the original waste that was treated and water produced during the microbial reactions in the digestion systems.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] This water may be released from the dewatering of the digestate or may be implicitly separate from the digestate.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] The wastewater exiting the anaerobic digestion facility will typically have elevated levels of biochemical oxygen demand (BOD) and chemical oxygen demand (COD).
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] These measures of the reactivity of the effluent indicate an ability to pollute.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] Some of this material is termed 'hard COD', meaning it cannot be accessed by the anaerobic bacteria for conversion into biogas.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] If this effluent were put directly into watercourses, it would negatively affect them by causing eutrophication.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] As such, further treatment of the wastewater is often required.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] This treatment will typically be an oxidation stage wherein air is passed through the water in a sequencing batch reactors or reverse osmosis unit.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] Reported scientific interest in the manufacturing of gas produced by the natural decomposition of organic matter dates from the 17th century, when Robert Boyle (1627–1691) and Stephen Hales (1677–1761) noted that disturbing the sediment of streams and lakes released flammable gas.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] In 1778, the Italian physicist Alessandro Volta (1745–1827), the father of electrochemistry, scientifically identified that gas as methane.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] In 1808 Sir Humphry Davy proved the presence of methane in the gases produced by cattle manure.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] The first known anaerobic digester was built in 1859 at a leper colony in Bombay in India.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] In 1895, the technology was developed in Exeter, England, where a septic tank was used to generate gas for the sewer gas destructor lamp, a type of gas lighting.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] Also in England, in 1904, the first dual-purpose tank for both sedimentation and sludge treatment was installed in Hampton, London.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] By the early 20th century, anaerobic digestion systems began to resemble the technology as it appears today.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] In 1906, Karl Imhoff created the Imhoff tank; an early form of anaerobic digester and model wastewater treatment system throughout the early 20th century.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] After 1920, closed tank systems began to replace the previously common use of anaerobic lagoons – covered earthen basins used to treat volatile solids.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] Research on anaerobic digestion began in earnest in the 1930s.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] Around the time of World War I, production from biofuels slowed as petroleum production increased and its uses were identified.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] While fuel shortages during World War II re-popularized anaerobic digestion, interest in the technology decreased again after the war ended.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] Similarly, the 1970s energy crisis sparked interest in anaerobic digestion.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] During the 1970s energy crisis, interest in small-scale and rural anaerobic digestion systems increased internationally.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] Ram Bux Singh developed and promoted early gobar gas (biogas) plants and contributed to the dissemination of anaerobic digestion technology for rural energy applications.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] His work was also referenced in publications such as *Mother Earth News*, which described him as “perhaps the father of methane development in the United States” during early biogas experimentation efforts.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] In addition to high energy prices, factors affecting the adoption of anaerobic digestion systems include receptivity to innovation, pollution penalties, policy incentives, and the availability of subsidies and funding opportunities.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] Today, anaerobic digesters are commonly found alongside farms to reduce nitrogen run-off from manure, or wastewater treatment facilities to reduce the costs of sludge disposal.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] Agricultural anaerobic digestion for energy production has become most popular in Germany, where there were 8,625 digesters in 2014.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] In the United Kingdom, there were 259 facilities by 2014, and 500 projects planned to become operational by 2019.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] In the United States, there were 191 operational plants across 34 states in 2012.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] Policy may explain why adoption rates are so different across these countries.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] Feed-in tariffs in Germany were enacted in 1991, also known as FIT, providing long-term contracts compensating investments in renewable energy generation.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] Consequently, between 1991 and 1998 the number of anaerobic digester plants in Germany grew from 20 to 517.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] In the late 1990s, energy prices in Germany varied and investors became unsure of the market's potential.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] The German government responded by amending FIT four times between 2000 and 2011, increasing tariffs and improving the profitability of anaerobic digestion, and resulting in reliable returns for biogas production and continued high adoption rates across the country.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] Anaerobic digesters have caused fish kills (e.g.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] River Mole, Devon, River Teifi, Afon Llynfi, and loss of human life (e.g.
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] Fortunately, according to one source, 'less than a dozen of them had consequences on humans'- for example, the incident at Rhadereistedt, Germany (4 dead).
[src:animal-product/anaerobic-digestion] Safety analyses have included a 2016 study compiled a database of 169 accidents involving ADs.
[src:animal-product/animal-by-products-regulations] The European Union's **Animal By-Products Regulations** (Regulation No 1069/2009) allows for the treatment of some animal by-products in composting and biogas plants (anaerobic digesters).
[src:animal-product/animal-by-products-regulations] The following article describes procedures required to allow solid outputs (compost, digestate) from composting plants and anaerobic digesters onto land in the United Kingdom.
[src:animal-product/animal-product] An **animal product** is any material derived from the body of a non-human animal or their excretions.
[src:animal-product/animal-product] Examples are meat, fat, blood, milk, eggs, honey, and less known products, such as isinglass, rennet, and cochineal.
[src:animal-product/animal-product] The word *animals* includes all species in the biological kingdom Animalia, except humans.
[src:animal-product/animal-product] This includes, for example, tetrapods, arthropods, and mollusks.
[src:animal-product/animal-product] Generally, products made from decomposed animals, such as petroleum, or crops grown in soil fertilized with animal remains or manure are not characterized as animal products.
[src:animal-product/animal-product] Products sourced from humans (e.g. breast milk) are not typically classified as animal products.
[src:animal-product/animal-product] Increased production and consumption over the past 50 years has led to widespread environmental and animal welfare impacts.
[src:animal-product/animal-product] These range from being linked to 80% of Amazonian deforestation to the welfare implications of using chick culling shredders on live day old-chicks for 7 billion of them each year.
[src:animal-product/animal-product] Several popular diet patterns prohibit the inclusion of some categories of animal products and may also limit the conditions of when other animal products may be permitted.
[src:animal-product/animal-product] This includes but not limited to secular diets; like, vegetarian, pescetarian, and paleolithic diets, as well as religious diets, such as kosher, halal, mahayana, macrobiotic, and sattvic diets.
[src:animal-product/animal-product] Other diets, such as vegan-vegetarian diets and all its subsets exclude any material of animal origin.
[src:animal-product/animal-product] Scholarly, the term animal source foods (ASFs) has been used to refer to these animal products and by-products collectively.
[src:animal-product/animal-product] In international trade legislation, the terminology **products of animal origin** (**POAO**) is used for referring to foods and goods that are derived from animals or have close relation to them.
[src:animal-product/animal-product] Animal husbandry has a significant impact on the world environment.
[src:animal-product/animal-product] Both production and consumption of animal products have increased rapidly.
[src:animal-product/animal-product] Since 1950, meat production has tripled, dairy production has doubled, and egg production has increased almost fourfold.
[src:animal-product/animal-product] Meanwhile, meat consumption has nearly doubled worldwide.
[src:animal-product/animal-product] Developing countries had a surge in meat consumption, particularly of monogastric livestock.
[src:animal-product/animal-product] Animal husbandry drives climate change, ocean acidification, and biodiversity loss, and kills 60 billion animals annually.
[src:animal-product/animal-product] It uses between 20 and 33% of the world's fresh water, Livestock, and the production of feed for them, occupy about a third of the Earth's ice-free land.
[src:animal-product/animal-product] Livestock production contributes to species extinction, desertification, and habitat destruction. and is the primary driver of the Holocene extinction.
[src:animal-product/animal-product] Some 70% of the agricultural land and 30% of Earth's land surface is involved directly or indirectly in animal husbandry.
[src:animal-product/animal-product] Habitat is destroyed by clearing forests and converting land to grow feed crops and for grazing, while predators and herbivores are frequently targeted because of a perceived threat to livestock profits; for example, animal husbandry causes up to 91% of the deforestation in the Amazon region.
[src:animal-product/animal-product] In addition, livestock produce greenhouse gases.
[src:animal-product/animal-product] Cows produce some 570 million cubic metres of methane per day, that accounts for 35 to 40% of the overall methane emissions of the planet.
[src:animal-product/animal-product] Further, livestock production is responsible for 65% of all human-related emissions of nitrous oxide.
[src:animal-product/animal-product] Since the 18th century, people have become increasingly concerned about the welfare of farm animals.
[src:animal-product/animal-product] Possible measures of welfare include longevity, behavior, physiology, reproduction, freedom from disease, and freedom from immunosuppression.
[src:animal-product/animal-product] An opposing view is that animals have rights, should not be regarded as property, are not necessary to use, and should never be used by humans.
[src:animal-product/animal-product] Live export of animals has risen to meet increased global demand for livestock, such as in the Middle East.
[src:animal-product/animal-product] Animal rights activists have objected to the long-distance transport of animals; one result was the banning of live exports from New Zealand in 2003.
[src:animal-product/animal-product] Farmed animals needs to eat more food than their products can deliver.
[src:animal-product/animal-product] Net animal losses are the difference between the calories in human-edible crops fed to animals and the calories returned in meat, dairy and fish.
[src:animal-product/animal-product] These losses are higher than all other conventional food losses combined.
[src:animal-product/animal-product] This is because on average livestock eat more human-edible food than their products provide.
[src:animal-product/animal-product] Research estimated that if the US would eat all human-edible plant food instead of feeding it to animals in order to eat their meat, dairy and eggs, it would free up enough food to feed an additional 350 million people.
[src:animal-product/animal-product] At a global level livestock is fed an average of 1738 kcal/person/day of human-edible food, and just 594 kcal/p/d of animal products return to the human food supply, a net loss of 66%.
[src:animal-product/animal-product] Animal by-products, as defined by the USDA, are products harvested or manufactured from livestock other than muscle meat.
[src:animal-product/animal-product] In the EU, animal by-products (ABPs) are defined somewhat more broadly, as materials from animals that people do not consume.
[src:animal-product/animal-product] Thus, chicken eggs for human consumption are considered by-products in the US but not France; whereas eggs destined for animal feed are classified as animal by-products in both countries.
[src:animal-product/animal-product] This does not in itself reflect on the condition, safety, or wholesomeness of the product.
[src:animal-product/animal-product] Animal by-products are carcasses and parts of carcasses from slaughterhouses, animal shelters, zoos and veterinarians, and products of animal origin not intended for human consumption, including catering waste.
[src:animal-product/animal-product] These products may go through a process known as rendering to be made into human and non-human foodstuffs, fats, and other material that can be sold to make commercial products such as cosmetics, paint, cleaners, polishes, glue, soap and ink.
[src:animal-product/animal-product] The sale of animal by-products allows the meat industry to compete economically with industries selling sources of vegetable protein.
[src:animal-product/animal-product] Slaughterhouse waste is defined as animal body parts cut off in the preparation of carcasses for use as food.
[src:animal-product/animal-product] This waste can come from several sources, including slaughterhouses, restaurants, stores and farms.
[src:animal-product/animal-product] In the UK, slaughterhouse waste is classed as category 3 risk waste in the Animal By-Products Regulations, with the exception of condemned meat which is classed as category 2 risk.
[src:animal-product/animal-product] The leftover pieces that come from the process of stripping meat from animals tends to get used for different purposes.
[src:animal-product/animal-product] One of them is to put these parts into pet food.
[src:animal-product/animal-product] Many large, well-known pet food brands use animal by-products as protein sources in their recipes.
[src:animal-product/animal-product] This can include animal feet, livers, lungs, heads, spleens, etc or an admixture in the form of meat and bone meal.
[src:animal-product/animal-product] These organs are usually not eaten by humans depending on culture, but are safe and nutritious for pets regardless.
[src:animal-product/animal-product] By-products can also include bad-looking pieces.
[src:animal-product/animal-product] They are always cooked (rendered) to kill pathogens.
[src:animal-product/animal-product] Just under half of all animal products in pet food is still human consumable, and some pet food makers advertise the lack of by-products to appeal to buyers, a move criticized for contributing to food waste and reducing sustainability.
[src:animal-product/animal] The animal kingdom is divided into five major clades, namely Porifera, Ctenophora, Placozoa, Cnidaria and Bilateria.
[src:animal-product/animal] The much smaller basal phylum Xenacoelomorpha have an uncertain position within Bilateria.
[src:animal-product/animal] Animals first appeared in the fossil record in the late Cryogenian period and diversified in the subsequent Ediacaran period in what is known as the Avalon explosion.
[src:animal-product/animal] Nearly all modern animal phyla first appeared in the fossil record as marine species during the Cambrian explosion, which began around 539 million years ago (Mya), and most classes during the Ordovician radiation 485.4 Mya.
[src:animal-product/animal] Common to all living animals, 6,331 groups of genes have been identified that may have arisen from a single common ancestor that lived about 650 Mya during the Cryogenian period.
[src:animal-product/animal] Historically, Aristotle divided animals into those with blood and those without.
[src:animal-product/animal] Carl Linnaeus created the first hierarchical biological classification for animals in 1758 with his *Systema Naturae*, which Jean-Baptiste Lamarck expanded into 14 phyla by 1809.
[src:animal-product/animal] In 1874, Ernst Haeckel divided the animal kingdom into the multicellular **Metazoa** (now synonymous with Animalia) and the Protozoa, single-celled organisms no longer considered animals.
[src:animal-product/animal] In modern times, the biological classification of animals relies on advanced techniques, such as molecular phylogenetics, which are effective at demonstrating the evolutionary relationships between taxa.
[src:animal-product/animal] Humans make use of many other animal species for food (including meat, eggs, and dairy products), for materials (such as leather, fur, and wool), as pets and as working animals for transportation, and services.
[src:animal-product/animal] Dogs, the first domesticated animal, have been used in hunting, in security and in warfare, as have horses, pigeons and birds of prey; while other terrestrial and aquatic animals are hunted for sports, trophies or profits.
[src:animal-product/animal] Non-human animals are also an important cultural element of human evolution, having appeared in cave arts and totems since the earliest times, and are frequently featured in mythology, religion, arts, literature, heraldry, politics, and sports.
[src:animal-product/animal] The word *animal* comes from the Latin noun *animal* of the same meaning, which is itself derived from Latin *animalis* 'having breath or soul'.
[src:animal-product/animal] The biological definition includes all members of the kingdom Animalia.
[src:animal-product/animal] In colloquial usage, the term *animal* is often used to refer only to nonhuman animals.
[src:animal-product/animal] The term *metazoa* is derived from Ancient Greek μετα *meta* 'after' (in biology, the prefix *meta-* stands for 'later') and ζῷᾰ *zōia* 'animals', plural of ζῷον *zōion* 'animal'.
[src:animal-product/animal] A **metazoan** is any member of the group *Metazoa*.
[src:animal-product/animal] Animals have several characteristics that they share with other living things.
[src:animal-product/animal] Animals are eukaryotic, multicellular, and aerobic, as are plants and fungi.
[src:animal-product/animal] Unlike plants and algae, which produce their own food, animals cannot produce their own food, a feature they share with fungi.
[src:animal-product/animal] Animals ingest organic material and digest it internally.
[src:animal-product/animal] Typically, there is an internal digestive chamber with either one opening (in Ctenophora, Cnidaria, and flatworms) or two openings (in most bilaterians).
[src:animal-product/animal] Animal development is controlled by Hox genes, which signal the times and places to develop structures such as body segments and limbs.
[src:animal-product/animal] During development, the animal extracellular matrix forms a relatively flexible framework upon which cells can move about and be reorganised into specialised tissues and organs, making the formation of complex structures possible, and allowing cells to be differentiated.
[src:animal-product/animal] The extracellular matrix may be calcified, forming structures such as shells, bones, and spicules.
[src:animal-product/animal] In contrast, the cells of other multicellular organisms (primarily algae, plants, and fungi) are held in place by cell walls, and so develop by progressive growth.
[src:animal-product/animal] Nearly all animals make use of some form of sexual reproduction.
[src:animal-product/animal] They produce haploid gametes by meiosis; the smaller, motile gametes are spermatozoa and the larger, non-motile gametes are ova.
[src:animal-product/animal] These fuse to form zygotes, which develop via mitosis into a hollow sphere, called a blastula.
[src:animal-product/animal] In sponges, blastula larvae swim to a new location, attach to the seabed, and develop into a new sponge.
[src:animal-product/animal] In most other groups, the blastula undergoes more complicated rearrangement.
[src:animal-product/animal] It first invaginates to form a gastrula with a digestive chamber and two separate germ layers, an external ectoderm and an internal endoderm.
[src:animal-product/animal] In most cases, a third germ layer, the mesoderm, also develops between them.
[src:animal-product/animal] These germ layers then differentiate to form tissues and organs.
[src:animal-product/animal] Repeated instances of mating with a close relative during sexual reproduction generally leads to inbreeding depression within a population due to the increased prevalence of harmful recessive traits.
[src:animal-product/animal] Animals have evolved numerous mechanisms for avoiding close inbreeding.
[src:animal-product/animal] Some animals are capable of asexual reproduction, which often results in a genetic clone of the parent.
[src:animal-product/animal] This may take place through fragmentation; budding, such as in *Hydra* and other cnidarians; or parthenogenesis, where fertile eggs are produced without mating, such as in aphids.
[src:animal-product/animal] Animals are categorised into ecological groups depending on their trophic levels and how they consume organic material.
[src:animal-product/animal] Such groupings include carnivores (further divided into subcategories such as piscivores, insectivores, ovivores, etc.), herbivores (subcategorised into folivores, graminivores, frugivores, granivores, nectarivores, algivores, etc.), omnivores, fungivores, scavengers/detritivores, and parasites.
[src:animal-product/animal] Interactions between animals of each biome form complex food webs within that ecosystem.
[src:animal-product/animal] In carnivorous or omnivorous species, predation is a consumer–resource interaction where the predator feeds on another organism, its prey, who often evolves anti-predator adaptations to avoid being fed upon.
[src:animal-product/animal] Selective pressures imposed on one another lead to an evolutionary arms race between predator and prey, resulting in various antagonistic/competitive coevolutions.
[src:animal-product/animal] Almost all multicellular predators are animals.
[src:animal-product/animal] Some consumers use multiple methods; for example, in parasitoid wasps, the larvae feed on the hosts' living tissues, killing them in the process, but the adults primarily consume nectar from flowers.
[src:animal-product/animal] Other animals may have very specific feeding behaviours, such as hawksbill sea turtles which mainly eat sponges.
[src:animal-product/animal] Most animals rely on biomass and bioenergy produced by plants and phytoplanktons (collectively called producers) through photosynthesis.
[src:animal-product/animal] Herbivores, as primary consumers, eat the plant material directly to digest and absorb the nutrients, while carnivores and other animals on higher trophic levels indirectly acquire the nutrients by eating the herbivores or other animals that have eaten the herbivores.
[src:animal-product/animal] Animals oxidise carbohydrates, lipids, proteins and other biomolecules in cellular respiration, which allows the animal to grow and to sustain basal metabolism and fuel other biological processes such as locomotion.
[src:animal-product/animal] Some benthic animals living close to hydrothermal vents and cold seeps on the dark sea floor consume organic matter produced through chemosynthesis (via oxidising inorganic compounds such as hydrogen sulfide) by archaea and bacteria.
[src:animal-product/animal] Animals originated in the ocean; all extant animal phyla, except for Micrognathozoa and Onychophora, feature at least some marine species.
[src:animal-product/animal] However, several lineages of arthropods begun to colonise land around the same time as land plants, between 510 and 471 million years ago, during the Late Cambrian or Early Ordovician periods.
[src:animal-product/animal] Vertebrates such as the lobe-finned fish *Tiktaalik* started to move on to land in the late Devonian, about 375 million years ago.
[src:animal-product/animal] Other notable animal groups that colonized land environments are Mollusca, Platyhelmintha, Annelida, Tardigrada, Onychophora, Rotifera, Nematoda.
[src:animal-product/animal] Animals occupy virtually all of earth's habitats and microhabitats, with faunas adapted to salt water, hydrothermal vents, fresh water, hot springs, swamps, forests, pastures, deserts, air, and the interiors of other organisms.
[src:animal-product/animal] Animals are however not particularly heat tolerant; very few of them can survive at constant temperatures above 50 °C (122 °F) or in the most extreme cold deserts of continental Antarctica.
[src:animal-product/animal] The collective global geomorphic influence of animals on the processes shaping the Earth's surface remains largely understudied, with most studies limited to individual species and well-known exemplars.
[src:animal-product/animal] The blue whale (*Balaenoptera musculus*) is the largest animal that has ever lived, weighing up to 190 tonnes and measuring up to 33.6 metres (110 ft) long.
[src:animal-product/animal] The largest extant terrestrial animal is the African bush elephant (*Loxodonta africana*), weighing up to 12.25 tonnes and measuring up to 10.67 metres (35.0 ft) long.
[src:animal-product/animal] The largest terrestrial animals that ever lived were titanosaur sauropod dinosaurs such as *Argentinosaurus*, which may have weighed as much as 73 tonnes, and *Supersaurus* which may have reached 39 metres.
[src:animal-product/animal] Several animals are microscopic; some Myxozoa (obligate parasites within the Cnidaria) never grow larger than 20 μm, and one of the smallest species (*Myxobolus shekel*) is no more than 8.5 μm when fully grown.
[src:animal-product/animal] The following table lists estimated numbers of described extant species for the major animal phyla, along with their principal habitats (terrestrial, fresh water, and marine), and free-living or parasitic ways of life.
[src:animal-product/animal] Species estimates shown here are based on numbers described scientifically; much larger estimates have been calculated based on various means of prediction, and these can vary wildly.
[src:animal-product/animal] For instance, around 25,000–27,000 species of nematodes have been described, while published estimates of the total number of nematode species include 10,000–20,000; 500,000; 10 million; and 100 million.
[src:animal-product/animal] Using patterns within the taxonomic hierarchy, the total number of animal species—including those not yet described—was calculated to be about 7.77 million in 2011.
[src:animal-product/animal] Evidence of animals is found as long ago as the Cryogenian period.
[src:animal-product/animal] 24-Isopropylcholestane (24-ipc) has been found in rocks from roughly 650 million years ago; it is only produced by sponges and pelagophyte algae.
[src:animal-product/animal] Its likely origin is from sponges based on molecular clock estimates for the origin of 24-ipc production in both groups.
[src:animal-product/animal] Analyses of pelagophyte algae consistently recover a Phanerozoic origin, while analyses of sponges recover a Neoproterozoic origin, consistent with the appearance of 24-ipc in the fossil record.
[src:animal-product/animal] The first body fossils of animals appear in the Ediacaran, represented by forms such as *Charnia* and *Spriggina*.
[src:animal-product/animal] It had long been doubted whether these fossils truly represented animals, but the discovery of the animal lipid cholesterol in fossils of *Dickinsonia* establishes their nature.
[src:animal-product/animal] Animals are thought to have originated under low-oxygen conditions, suggesting that they were capable of living entirely by anaerobic respiration, but as they became specialised for aerobic metabolism they became fully dependent on oxygen in their environments.
[src:animal-product/animal] Many animal phyla first appear in the fossil record during the Cambrian explosion, starting about 539 million years ago, in beds such as the Burgess Shale.
[src:animal-product/animal] Extant phyla in these rocks include molluscs, brachiopods, onychophorans, tardigrades, arthropods, echinoderms and hemichordates, along with numerous now-extinct forms such as the predatory *Anomalocaris*.
[src:animal-product/animal] The apparent suddenness of the event may however be an artefact of the fossil record, rather than showing that all these animals appeared simultaneously.
[src:animal-product/animal] That view is supported by the discovery of *Auroralumina attenboroughii*, the earliest known Ediacaran crown-group cnidarian (557–562 mya, some 20 million years before the Cambrian explosion) from Charnwood Forest, England.
[src:animal-product/animal] It is thought to be one of the earliest predators, catching small prey with its nematocysts as modern cnidarians do.
[src:animal-product/animal] Some palaeontologists have suggested that animals appeared much earlier than the Cambrian explosion, possibly as early as 1 billion years ago.
[src:animal-product/animal] Early fossils that might represent animals appear for example in the 665-million-year-old rocks of the Trezona Formation of South Australia.
[src:animal-product/animal] These fossils are interpreted as most probably being early sponges.
[src:animal-product/animal] Trace fossils such as tracks and burrows found in the Tonian period (from 1 gya) may indicate the presence of triploblastic worm-like animals, roughly as large (about 5 mm wide) and complex as earthworms.
[src:animal-product/animal] However, similar tracks are produced by the giant single-celled protist *Gromia sphaerica*, so the Tonian trace fossils may not indicate early animal evolution.
[src:animal-product/animal] Around the same time, the layered mats of microorganisms called stromatolites decreased in diversity, perhaps due to grazing by newly evolved animals.
[src:animal-product/animal] Objects such as sediment-filled tubes that resemble trace fossils of the burrows of wormlike animals have been found in 1.2 gya rocks in North America, in 1.5 gya rocks in Australia and North America, and in 1.7 gya rocks in Australia.
[src:animal-product/animal] Their interpretation as having an animal origin is disputed, as they might be water-escape or other structures.
[src:animal-product/animal] Animals are monophyletic, meaning they are derived from a common ancestor.
[src:animal-product/animal] Animals are the sister group to the choanoflagellates, with which they form the Choanozoa.
[src:animal-product/animal] Ros-Rocher and colleagues (2021) trace the origins of animals to unicellular ancestors, providing the external phylogeny shown in the cladogram.
[src:animal-product/animal] Uncertainty of relationships is indicated with dashed lines.
[src:animal-product/animal] The animal clade had certainly originated by 650 mya, and may have come into being as much as 800 mya, based on molecular clock evidence for different phyla.
[src:animal-product/animal] The relationships at the base of the animal tree have been debated.
[src:animal-product/animal] Other than Ctenophora, the Bilateria and Cnidaria are the only groups with symmetry, and other evidence shows they are closely related.
[src:animal-product/animal] In addition to sponges, Placozoa has no symmetry and was often considered a "missing link" between protists and multicellular animals.
[src:animal-product/animal] The presence of hox genes in Placozoa shows that they were once more complex.
[src:animal-product/animal] The Porifera (sponges) have long been assumed to be sister to the rest of the animals, but there is evidence that the Ctenophora may be in that position.
[src:animal-product/animal] Molecular phylogenetics has supported both the sponge-sister and ctenophore-sister hypotheses.
[src:animal-product/animal] Sponges are physically very distinct from other animals, and were long thought to have diverged first, representing the oldest animal phylum and forming a sister clade to all other animals.
[src:animal-product/animal] Despite their morphological dissimilarity with all other animals, genetic evidence suggests sponges may be more closely related to other animals than the comb jellies are.
[src:animal-product/animal] Sponges lack the complex organisation found in most other animal phyla; their cells are differentiated, but in most cases not organised into distinct tissues, unlike all other animals.
[src:animal-product/animal] Sponges are almost entirely sessile in their adult stage.
[src:animal-product/animal] Sponges lack a digestive, circulatory, respiratory, or excretory system.
[src:animal-product/animal] Instead, they rely on the flow of water through their bodies to perform these functions.
[src:animal-product/animal] Many have adapted a hollow structure to facilitate the flow of water through their bodies.
[src:animal-product/animal] They typically feed by drawing in water through pores, filtering out small particles of food.
[src:animal-product/animal] They absorb oxygen dissolved in water, and they release carbon dioxide and nitrogenous waste into water that flows through them.
[src:animal-product/animal] Sponges can reproduce sexually and asexually.
[src:animal-product/animal] Asexual reproduction happens through a variety of mechanisms including by fragmentation, where a piece of the sponge splits off and reestablishes somewhere else.
[src:animal-product/animal] For sexual reproduction, most sponges are hermaphrodites, they produce both egg and sperm cells.
[src:animal-product/animal] Comb jellies, members of Ctenophora, are radially symmetric and have digestive chambers with a single opening, which serves as both mouth and anus.
[src:animal-product/animal] Ctenophora have distinct tissues, but these are not organised into discrete organs.
[src:animal-product/animal] They move using large arrays of cilia, called swimming plates.
[src:animal-product/animal] They have are unique in having colloblasts, structures on their tentacles that help them catch prey.
[src:animal-product/animal] They have nerve cells, but lack a brain or central nervous system.
[src:animal-product/animal] Instead their nerves are arranged into a nerve net.
[src:animal-product/animal] Their nerves are very different from those of other animals, and evidence suggests that their nerves developed independently of the nerves of other animals.
[src:animal-product/animal] Like Ctenophora, Cnidaria are radially symmetric and have digestive chambers with a single opening, which serves as both mouth and anus.
[src:animal-product/animal] They also have distinct tissues that are not organised into discrete organs.
[src:animal-product/animal] Members of the group Anthozoa, such as sea anemones, coral, and sea pens only are sessile polyps.
[src:animal-product/animal] Most members of Medusozoa, including jellyfish and most hydrozoans, have a polyp form as well, but also have a motile medusae stage.
[src:animal-product/animal] The medusae stage are commonly known as jellyfish.
[src:animal-product/animal] Cnidaria are diploblastic, having only two main germ layers, ectoderm and endoderm.
[src:animal-product/animal] The tiny placozoans have no permanent digestive chamber and no symmetry; they superficially resemble amoebae.
[src:animal-product/animal] Their phylogeny is poorly defined, and under active research.
[src:animal-product/animal] The remaining animals, the great majority—comprising some 29 phyla and over a million species—form the Bilateria clade, which have a bilaterally symmetric body plan.
[src:animal-product/animal] The Bilateria are triploblastic, with three well-developed germ layers, and their tissues form distinct organs.
[src:animal-product/animal] The digestive chamber has two openings, a mouth and an anus, and in the Nephrozoa there is an internal body cavity, a coelom or pseudocoelom.
[src:animal-product/animal] These animals have a head end (anterior) and a tail end (posterior), a back (dorsal) surface and a belly (ventral) surface, and a left and a right side.
[src:animal-product/animal] A modern consensus phylogenetic tree for the Bilateria is shown below.
[src:animal-product/animal] Having a front end means that this part of the body encounters stimuli, such as food, favouring cephalisation, the development of a head with sense organs and a mouth.
[src:animal-product/animal] Many bilaterians have a combination of circular muscles that constrict the body, making it longer, and an opposing set of longitudinal muscles, that shorten the body; these enable soft-bodied animals with a hydrostatic skeleton to move by peristalsis.
[src:animal-product/animal] They also have a gut that extends through the basically cylindrical body from mouth to anus.
[src:animal-product/animal] Many bilaterian phyla have primary larvae which swim with cilia and have an apical organ containing sensory cells.
[src:animal-product/animal] However, over evolutionary time, descendant spaces have evolved which have lost one or more of each of these characteristics.
[src:animal-product/animal] For example, adult echinoderms are radially symmetric (unlike their larvae), while some parasitic worms have extremely simplified body structures.
[src:animal-product/animal] Genetic studies have considerably changed zoologists' understanding of the relationships within the Bilateria.
[src:animal-product/animal] Most appear to belong to two major lineages, the protostomes and the deuterostomes.
[src:animal-product/animal] It is often suggested that the basalmost bilaterians are the Xenacoelomorpha, with all other bilaterians belonging to the subclade Nephrozoa.
[src:animal-product/animal] However, this suggestion has been contested, with other studies finding that xenacoelomorphs are more closely related to Ambulacraria than to other bilaterians.
[src:animal-product/animal] Protostomes and deuterostomes differ in several ways.
[src:animal-product/animal] Early in development, deuterostome embryos undergo radial cleavage during cell division, while many protostomes (the Spiralia) undergo spiral cleavage.
[src:animal-product/animal] Animals from both groups possess a complete digestive tract, but in protostomes the first opening of the embryonic gut develops into the mouth, and the anus forms secondarily.
[src:animal-product/animal] In deuterostomes, the anus forms first while the mouth develops secondarily.
[src:animal-product/animal] Most protostomes have schizocoelous development, where cells simply fill in the interior of the gastrula to form the mesoderm.
[src:animal-product/animal] In deuterostomes, the mesoderm forms by enterocoelic pouching, through invagination of the endoderm.
[src:animal-product/animal] The main deuterostome taxa are the Ambulacraria and the Chordata.
[src:animal-product/animal] Ambulacraria are exclusively marine and include acorn worms, starfish, sea urchins, and sea cucumbers.
[src:animal-product/animal] The chordates are dominated by the vertebrates (animals with backbones), which consist of fishes, amphibians, reptiles, birds, and mammals.
[src:animal-product/animal] The protostomes include the Ecdysozoa, named after their shared trait of ecdysis, growth by moulting, Among the largest ecdysozoan phyla are the arthropods and the nematodes.
[src:animal-product/animal] The rest of the protostomes are in the Spiralia, named for their pattern of developing by spiral cleavage in the early embryo.
[src:animal-product/animal] Major spiralian phyla include the annelids and molluscs.
[src:animal-product/animal] In the classical era, Aristotle divided animals, based on his own observations, into those with blood (roughly, the vertebrates) and those without.
[src:animal-product/animal] In 1758, Carl Linnaeus created the first hierarchical classification in his *Systema Naturae*.
[src:animal-product/animal] In his original scheme, the animals were one of three kingdoms, divided into the classes of Vermes, Insecta, Pisces, Amphibia, Aves, and Mammalia.
[src:animal-product/animal] Since then, the last four have all been subsumed into a single phylum, the Chordata, while his Insecta (which included the crustaceans and arachnids) and Vermes have been renamed or broken up.
[src:animal-product/animal] The process was begun in 1793 by Jean-Baptiste de Lamarck, who called the Vermes *une espèce de chaos* ('a chaotic mess') and split the group into three new phyla: worms, echinoderms, and polyps (which contained corals and jellyfish).
[src:animal-product/animal] By 1809, in his *Philosophie Zoologique*, Lamarck had created nine phyla apart from vertebrates (where he still had four phyla: mammals, birds, reptiles, and fish) and molluscs, namely cirripedes, annelids, crustaceans, arachnids, insects, worms, radiates, polyps, and infusorians.
[src:animal-product/animal] This division into four was followed by the embryologist Karl Ernst von Baer in 1828, the zoologist Louis Agassiz in 1857, and the comparative anatomist Richard Owen in 1860.
[src:animal-product/animal] In 1874, Ernst Haeckel divided the animal kingdom into two subkingdoms: Metazoa (multicellular animals, with five phyla: coelenterates, echinoderms, articulates, molluscs, and vertebrates) and Protozoa (single-celled animals), including a sixth animal phylum, sponges.
[src:animal-product/animal] The protozoa were later moved to the former kingdom Protista, leaving only the Metazoa as a synonym of Animalia.
[src:animal-product/animal] The human population exploits a large number of other animal species for food, both of domesticated livestock species in animal husbandry and, mainly at sea, by hunting wild species.
[src:animal-product/animal] Marine fish of many species are caught commercially for food.
[src:animal-product/animal] A smaller number of species are farmed commercially.
[src:animal-product/animal] Humans and their livestock make up more than 90% of the biomass of all terrestrial vertebrates, and almost as much as all insects combined.
[src:animal-product/animal] Invertebrates including cephalopods, crustaceans, insects—principally bees and silkworms—and bivalve or gastropod molluscs are hunted or farmed for food, fibres.
[src:animal-product/animal] Chickens, cattle, sheep, pigs, and other animals are raised as livestock for meat across the world.
[src:animal-product/animal] Animal fibres such as wool and silk are used to make textiles, while animal sinews have been used as lashings and bindings, and leather is widely used to make shoes and other items.
[src:animal-product/animal] Animals have been hunted and farmed for their fur to make items such as coats and hats.
[src:animal-product/animal] Dyestuffs including carmine (cochineal), shellac, and kermes have been made from the bodies of insects.
[src:animal-product/animal] Working animals including cattle and horses have been used for work and transport from the first days of agriculture.
[src:animal-product/animal] Animals such as the fruit fly *Drosophila melanogaster* serve a major role in science as experimental models.
[src:animal-product/animal] Animals have been used to create vaccines since their discovery in the 18th century.
[src:animal-product/animal] Some medicines such as the cancer drug trabectedin are based on toxins or other molecules of animal origin.
[src:animal-product/animal] People have used hunting dogs to help chase down and retrieve animals, and birds of prey to catch birds and mammals, while tethered cormorants have been used to catch fish.
[src:animal-product/animal] Poison dart frogs have been used to poison the tips of blowpipe darts.
[src:animal-product/animal] A wide variety of animals are kept as pets, from invertebrates such as tarantulas, octopuses, and praying mantises, reptiles such as snakes and chameleons, and birds including canaries, parakeets, and parrots all finding a place.
[src:animal-product/animal] However, the most kept pet species are mammals, namely dogs, cats, and rabbits.
[src:animal-product/animal] There is a tension between the role of animals as companions to humans, and their existence as individuals with rights of their own.
[src:animal-product/animal] A wide variety of terrestrial and aquatic animals are hunted for sport.
[src:animal-product/animal] The signs of the Western and Chinese zodiacs are based on animals.
[src:animal-product/animal] In China and Japan, the butterfly has been seen as the personification of a person's soul, and in classical representation the butterfly is also the symbol of the soul.
[src:animal-product/animal] Animals have been the subjects of art from the earliest times, both historical, as in ancient Egypt, and prehistoric, as in the cave paintings at Lascaux.
[src:animal-product/animal] Major animal paintings include Albrecht Dürer's 1515 *The Rhinoceros*, and George Stubbs's c.
[src:animal-product/animal] Insects, birds and mammals play roles in literature and film, such as in giant bug movies.
[src:animal-product/animal] Animals including insects and mammals feature in mythology and religion.
[src:animal-product/animal] The scarab beetle was sacred in ancient Egypt, and the cow is sacred in Hinduism.
[src:animal-product/animal] Among other mammals, deer, horses, lions, bats, bears, and wolves are the subjects of myths and worship.
